	Volume = {106},
	Number = {28},
	Pages = {11433-11438},
	Month = {JUL 14},
	Abstract = {Networks describe a variety of interacting complex systems in social
	science, biology, and information technology. Usually the nodes of real
	networks are identified not only by their connections but also by some
	other characteristics. Examples of characteristics of nodes can be age,
	gender, or nationality of a person in a social network, the abundance of
	proteins in the cell taking part in protein-interaction networks, or the
	geographical position of airports that are connected by directed
	flights. Integrating the information on the connections of each node
	with the information about its characteristics is crucial to
	discriminating between the essential and negligible characteristics of
	nodes for the structure of the network. In this paper we propose a
	general indicator T, based on entropy measures, to quantify the
	dependence of a network's structure on a given set of features. We apply
