	Pages = {16-29},
	Month = {MAR},
	Abstract = {Prior research argues that religious homophily in social networks is a
	product of overlapping interests and activities unintentionally leading
	to relationships or the intentional seeking of relationships with people
	of similar religious beliefs. This article advances research on
	religious homophily by including the role that exclusive theological
	beliefs play in explaining religious homophily among friends. We lay out
	three propositions for individual-, congregational-, and cross-level
	effects on the relationship between exclusive theology and embeddedness
	within one's congregation. Using multilevel models and data from the
	U.S. Congregational Life Survey (USCLS), we find support for our three
	propositions. We discuss our findings in terms of how exclusive
	theologies may contribute to bonding forms of social capital, but limit
