	Year = {2015},
	Volume = {41},
	Pages = {113-126},
	Month = {MAY},
	Abstract = {A growing number of studies indicate that aspects of psychology and
	cognition influence network structure, but much remains to be learned
	about how network information is stored and retrieved from memory. Are
	networks recalled as dyads, as triads, or more generally as sub-groups?
	We employ an experimental design coupled with exponential random graph
	models to address this issue. We find that respondents flexibly encode
	social information as triads or groups, depending on the network, but
	not as dyads. This supports prior research showing that networks are
	stored using ``compression heuristics{''}, but also provides evidence of
	cognitive flexibility in the process of encoding relational information.
