	Month = {JAN},
	Abstract = {By expanding Coleman's theory of the intergenerational conversion
	process, social network theory, and Bourdieu's cultural capital theory,
	the author identified four components of family capital that are
	important for the educational attainment of children: human capital,
	financial capital, social capital, and cultural capital. Furthermore,
	unlike the conventional approach that focuses on parent-child
	relationships in families, the author defined social capital to include
	social relationships and networks outside the family that parents can
	use. The relative importance of each component of family capital for a
	child's education is illustrated by a case study of socialist
	Czechoslovakia in which social capital was operationalized by membership
	in the Communist Party. The study found that in addition to each
	component's independent influences on children's educational attainment,
