	Volume = {52},
	Number = {11},
	Pages = {1507-1530},
	Month = {JUL},
	Abstract = {Critics have argued that the term social capital is too vague or general
	to be a useful concept. Recognizing the need for clarification, the
	authors distill the conceptual discussions about social capital to argue
	that there are three components-network structure, trust and
	reciprocity, and resources-that are associated with but vary in degree
	and salience for all forms of social capital. These three components
	should be considered continua along which the forms of social capital
	can vary. A fourth continuum is between micro and macro levels of social
	capital. Locating particular examples of social capital along these
	continua opens the possibility to compare different types of social
	capital and to develop and test theories about how they are related to
	each other. The authors also describe a simulation study to illustrate
	how simulation can facilitate understanding of the linkages among
