	Journal = {PLOS ONE},
	Year = {2015},
	Volume = {10},
	Number = {10},
	Month = {OCT 23},
	Abstract = {Nature shows as human beings live and grow inside social structures.
	This assumption allows us to explain and explore how it may shape most
	of our behaviours and choices, and why we are not just blindly driven by
	instincts: our decisions are based on more complex cognitive reasons,
	based on our connectedness on different spaces. Thus, human cooperation
	emerges from this complex nature of social network. Our paper, focusing
	on the evolutionary dynamics, is intended to explore how and why it
	happens, and what kind of impact is caused by homophily among people. We
	investigate the evolution of human cooperation using evolutionary game
	theory on multiplex. Multiplexity, as an extra dimension of analysis,
	allows us to unveil the hidden dynamics and observe non-trivial patterns
	within a population across network layers. More importantly, we find a
	striking role of homophily, as the higher the homophily between
	individuals, the quicker is the convergence towards cooperation in the
	social dilemma. The simulation results, conducted both macroscopically
	and microscopically across the network layers in the multiplex, show
	quantitatively the role of homophily in human cooperation.},
