	Year = {2019},
	Volume = {63},
	Number = {12, SI},
	Pages = {1708-1727},
	Month = {NOV},
	Abstract = {Nongovernmental organizations (NGOs), like most strategic communicators,
	are challenged with breaking through the saturated international media
	environment as they attempt to influence public opinion. Yet, before
	strategic communicators can build an agenda, they must get attention
	from the public. The current study examined how NGOs' network positions
	in the public Twitter discussion of the global refugee crisis influenced
	the public engagement NGOs received during two news events. Drawing from
	network theory and research, we posed two parallel sets of hypotheses.
	First, we predicted that NGOs with characteristics of ``star{''} network
	structures will be well-situated in the network to garner attention.
	Second, we hypothesized that the ``village{''} around an NGO also
	contributes to capturing attention. The results from our regressions
