	Month = {JUL},
	Abstract = {We propose an intuitive way of how to measure segregation in social and
	spatial networks. Using random walks, we define the segregation index as
	the probability that an individual meets an individual from the same
	social group. The segregation index is a generalization of the isolation
	index and a homophily index introduced in Currarini, Jackson, and Pin
	(2009), and it has a closed-form relation to PageRank that facilitates
	its computation. We also show that the Spectral Segregation Index
	proposed by Echenique and Fryer (2007) is not continuous with respect to
	the network structure. Finally, we apply the measure to Spanish census
	data and to citations data from economics, and rationalize the index as
