	Year = {2021},
	Volume = {66},
	Pages = {10-25},
	Month = {JUL},
	Abstract = {How do new scientific ideas diffuse? Computational studies reveal how
	network structures facilitate or obstruct diffusion; qualitative studies
	demonstrate that diffusion entails the continuous translation and
	transformation of ideas. This article bridges these computational and
	qualitative approaches to study diffusion as a complex process of
	continuous adaptation. As a case study, we analyze the spread of
	Granovetter's Strength of Weak Ties hypothesis, published in American
	Journal of Sociology in 1973. Through network analysis, topic modeling
	and a close reading of a diffusion network created using Web of Science
	data, we study how different communities in this network interpret and
	develop Granovetter's hypothesis in distinct ways. We further trace how
