	Year = {2020},
	Volume = {7},
	Number = {1},
	Month = {DEC 11},
	Abstract = {This article examines the scope of pro-Kremlin disinformation about
	Crimea. I deploy content analysis and a social network approach to
	analyze tweets related to the region. I find that pro-Kremlin
	disinformation partially penetrated the Twitter debates about Crimea.
	However, these disinformation narratives are accompanied by a much
	larger wave of information that disagrees with the disinformation and
	are less prevalent in relative terms. The impact of Russian
	state-controlled news outlets-which are frequent sources of pro-Kremlin
	disinformation-is concentrated in one, highly popular news outlet, RT.
	The few, popular Russian news media have to compete with many popular
	Western media outlets. As a result, the combined impact of Russian
	state-controlled outlets is relatively low when comparing to its Western
