	Number = {2},
	Pages = {154-172},
	Abstract = {The present study uses egocentric networks collected from youth (aged
	14-24) incarcerated with California's Division of Juvenile Justice to
	examine the composition and structure of youth's friendship networks
	during periods of incarceration and to test the relationship between
	friendship and institutional misconduct. Tests of network homophily
	reveal that youth networks report more diversity across both
	racial/ethnic categories and gang membership than expected from
	non-network research about inmate organization. Regression results
	indicate that youth who stated they had no close friendships within the
	facility had a lower rate of institutional misconduct post-interview
	compared to those who nominated peer friendships. The current study
