	Volume = {5},
	Number = {3},
	Pages = {182-202},
	Month = {NOV},
	Abstract = {Cancer is a life-changing condition for many American seniors, and a
	growing body of literature is assessing the mental health implications
	of living with the disease. This article builds from the well-known
	buffering hypothesis with insights from recent cancer research to
	investigate whether social networks moderate the association between
	cancer and mental health for older men and women. Analyses use two waves
	of survey data (2005-2006 and 2011) from the National Social Life,
	Health, and Aging Project (N = 1,367), enabling us to track new
	diagnoses of cancer and network dynamics over time. Consistent with a
	stress-buffering pattern, larger and growing networks were associated
